=begin pod

=head1 9. Next Steps

=head2 What you learned

=item Define a schema as a Raku Grammar with named tokens
=item Use C<LLM::Functions> to normalize free-form text to your DSL
=item Parse the DSL with Grammar + Actions + C<Actionable>
=item Get typed, validated structured output
=item Build schema-driven pipelines instead of fragile regex or prompt hacks

=head2 Things to explore next

=defn Nested schemas
Add a C<token address> subrule with its own sub-tokens, and a nested class
inside C<Booking>. The C<Actionable> role composes naturally.

=defn Tool calling
Wire C<parse-booking> as a tool in an C<LLM::Functions> agent so the LLM
can invoke it mid-conversation.

=defn Streaming structured output
Parse incrementally as the LLM streams tokens — useful when the DSL is long.

=defn Retries on validation failure
Catch a failed parse, feed the raw LLM output back with an error message, and
ask it to correct the DSL. Usually one retry is enough.

=defn Integration with agent workflows
Use the structured C<Booking> / C<Ticket> objects as typed messages passed
between agents in a multi-step pipeline.

=defn The Slangify Playground
Paste any Grammar + Actions pair into L<https://slangify.org> to test and
share your DSL interactively — no local install needed.

=head2 Further reading

=item L<Slangify::Tutorial source|https://github.com/librasteve/Slangify-Tutorial>
